The first virtual provider is coming to the Czech Republic this year.
- Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech providers offer virtually all services, as they are also offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classics at lower prices.
Maybe he won't be waiting long.
We have often reported on Mobil.cz that the Czech mobile phone providers work among the most expensive in Europe.
This was also confirmed by the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> telecommunications authority, which pointed out that the price for an SMS here is higher than in the rest of the European Union.
After the European Commission's final steps in the area of regulation of roaming charges, there is so likely to be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of the Czech mobile phone providers SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
Why are prices in the Czech Republic so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks the competition that really makes a statement.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, but in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
The mobile operators, on the other hand, like to brag about the fact that there is extremely much competition in the Czech market.
Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xA1>k, Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), who has often stated in the past that there is no room for another provider in the Czech Republic, is often obliged to do so.
It is likely true that a classic provider with its own network will no longer have very many opportunities (by the way, he would probably hardly even find frequencies).
But there is one more option – a virtual provider.
Especially the entry of virtual providers into the mobile radio market brought with it a significant price reduction, to which the classic mobile phone providers had to respond.
There were similar voices in the UK before companies like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the market as in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
By the way, you don’t have to look for examples for long.
In February this year, we reported on the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to attract more than 100 thousand customers and thus to become the country’s fifth largest provider.
Behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic, among others.
The advantage of virtual providers is that you can focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to work effectively, virtual providers need far fewer customers than a classic provider.
They do not require relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers typically profile themselves as low-cost firms – they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less extensive service offering.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a pretty good move to bet on a non-cliché target group.
This service is specifically geared towards men.
“Real guys choose Mobilking – the provider they like and can trust,” said David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, the provider of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could be found in the Czech Republic.
Vodafone spokesperson Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> also doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the service offer."
In the Czech Republic chancenlos, the mobile phone providers think
However, it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile provider conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be mobile.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not look particularly hopeful.
It will be more likely to enter the market of mobile in other countries of our region," Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>kov<0xC3><0xA1>, spokeswoman for the financial group Penta, told Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything to ensure that no potential competitor is created.
Their interest in starting a virtual mobile provider has long been demonstrated by the GTS Novera Group, which wants to take another step to become a real competitor of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
“We have a great interest in providing our customers not only fixed-line, but also mobile telecommunication services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this option with all Czech mobile providers.
With some of them, we have already been able to make progress in the negotiations,” said Pavel Kaidl, Group spokesperson.
Maybe better times are coming now.
Unofficial information shows that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
Until now, however, this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
“At the moment, we do not assume that there is room for a full-fledged virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market has a high specificity compared to other markets.
So far, no subject has addressed us with a complex and serious project in this area," says Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> from the press department of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2 in his statement to Mobil.cz.
Other providers also point to the specifics of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> rarely adds in line with O2's statement: "So far, we have not found a viable and mutually beneficial project on which to build on."
And she adds: “On the network of T-Mobile, hardly a virtual provider will appear by the end of the year.
At this point, we would have to have a concrete offer in order to be able to think so short-term.”
Vodafone focuses its attention on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> said: “We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
This is exactly what we consider the best from the customer’s point of view.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile internet.”
Responsible authorities - with the suppliers hand in hand
It is easy to understand the actions of the mobile providers, another provider would call more competition, which would lead to falling prices and thus also to a decrease in profits.
So why should such a competitor be allowed to enter the market?
The fact that providers can pull on a string when it comes to something also proves the long way around the emergence of U:fon.
Probably the strongest pressure in the direction of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> came when U:fon came on the market, from the company T-Mobile.
This is also evidenced by the publicly available information from the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> websites.
But now U:fon is suitable as an argument why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> commented: “The competitive environment of the mobile market has recently also been strengthened by the market entry of a fourth mobile provider.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player in the market itself and in particular its services would make high demands."
In view of this approach, however, the mobile operator is amazed by the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities.
This is not just about the attitude of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which unfortunately, unlike the UK and other highly developed countries, does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
It is owned exclusively by the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
This, however, relates to this whole problem, its very typical attitude.
“The entry into the market of a virtual mobile provider would be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile provider and a virtual provider through the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential stakeholders was probably not interesting enough for the classic providers," Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa of the Department of Foreign Relations of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS said in his response to our request.
Representatives of the providers would not be surprised by such a wording.
This is more than worrying, from an authority that represents consumer interests and, among other things, is to ensure that no one abuses its position in the market.
In particular, when Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa adds: "In abroad, where virtual providers work quite normally, it is to be observed that their market entry has contributed to a price reduction in mobile telephone services."
However, it is likely that pressure on the proper functioning of the market and a price reduction are not in the interests of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
It is truly shocking in this case that the three mobile providers are almost already in agreement, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just like the exact same gasoline price at the gas stations, it is certainly just a coincidence and the consequence of a tough competition.
“The Authority has not discovered any signs in this case that indicate an action directed against competition, and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way in the matter.
None of the providers has a dominant market position, so he also does not have the corresponding increased responsibility for his trading in the market.
The necessary tools for opening up the mobile market for virtual providers are probably also missing from the regulatory authority for telecommunications," Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, elaborated by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, after telecommunications from the point of view of economic competition is a single market.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile operators has a dominant position.
Some legal experts, however, offer a different view - for the market entry of a virtual provider, the approval of the network operator is always necessary.
And the mobile provider has, logically, the monopoly for its network.
This means that it necessarily occupies a dominant position in a particular segment.
However, even if one does not agree with this argument, there should be at least one warning for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that three mobile providers are strikingly similar.
In doing so, complaints by a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) demonstrate that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all providers.
The transfer of responsibility to <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is then a fairly common trick in telecommunications services, with which the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recently adopted telecommunications law has not succeeded in enforcing <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>'s expansion of competences in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts have promised an improvement in the situation.
The representatives of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS need to know this all too well, but they probably have different interests.
It's okay when no one's looking
First of all, the functioning of any pseudo-virtual provider, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
They are companies that issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but only partially public.
Usually, these are companies that operate in the field of multilevel marketing.
Own mobile phone services include Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach selected ones.
The joke of the matter is that the company appears to the operator as a classic company customer who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he then receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile phone providers prohibit a similar kind of resale.
"If there are cases that you describe, then it can be a violation of the contractual conditions that we will then deal with, which can lead to an end to cooperation with the relevant society," Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> replied to our question on this issue.
However, it is quite unlikely that something like this will not be talked about by the managers of the mobile service providers.
Especially in the case of the three mentioned companies, it can be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such a procedure.
As a result of the activities of these companies, they do not receive negligible profits, but at the same time, unlike the actual virtual providers, they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> draws attention to possible problems: "The law allows for such types of speculation, however, the services of these companies are only used by a very small percentage of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone does not run on their name, so they cannot fully have it like the normal customers of the mobile providers."
This alone, however, should at least happen strangely.
In addition, another question opens up for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
When mobile providers close their eyes to such an act, why do they lock themselves against a virtual provider?
It is added that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has quite strong competences to detect such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to satisfy itself with the declaration of the providers that they knew nothing about it and their terms and conditions would prohibit this.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has been pointed out several times in the text, the market entry of virtual providers resulted in a significant price decline in the various services.
Virtually in all countries where virtual providers have originated, the classic providers have tried to prevent their emergence practically more or less.
The arguments they used were practically identical - a too small or too saturated market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
However, in the high-developed countries, the regulatory bodies are intervening at these very moments, which in no way tried to protect the interests of mobile providers, but those of their customers.
Whether through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created, and this followed further.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are throwing themselves all over the case like a hot potato.
On the basis of our experience, we cannot escape the impression that ambiguity in the competencies in these cases is more than beneficial.
But we do not throw the flint into the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider appears soon, the Czech mobile market may soon be back in motion.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile provider, the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS will not remain inactive when it comes to refusing (discriminating) other interested parties.
And then the Czechs will finally not be more expensive to call than the rest of Europe.
