I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness, without me or anyone else being able to prove this until now where we can’t even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope, since all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, as soon as we turn to other species and trim questions of feeling or consciousness in general, we enter immobile terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same as many other animals: it faces dead, flees, or attacks.
People behave similarly, from which some scientists suggest a similar subjective experience.
I don't believe it, though.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to that of animals.
On the one hand, the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the lateral prefrontal cortex (because of its participation in short-term memory and the execution/control functions).
This broad region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and seems to be completely lacking in other creatures.
At least for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including the knowledge of who we are and the ability to plan and decide, there is reason to assume that man is even different from the other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity may lie in the linguistic nature of man: since such a large part of his experience is connected with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness did not depend on language, it would certainly influence it, so that animal consciousness, whatever its nature may be, is likely to be very different from most of our states of consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness might look like in other animals.
If, as something internal and subjective, it can neither be measured nor analyzed on the basis of our own experience because of the special hardware, then its research presents us with great problems.
Most of my statements refer to the content of the conscious experience, but there is another aspect of the consciousness, which may be more scientifically accessible.
One could examine the processes of consciousness of animals without regard to their contents, and this is precisely what happens in studies on the short-term memory of primates, especially in the example of visualization.
But with this approach, followed by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, one relies more on the neural correlates of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: both may or may not be identical.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex for the attainment of visualization.
What is the result of the sensations?
I lead them back to the fact that an emotional system like that of fear is activated in a conscious brain of its own activity.
So what we call “fear” is the mental state in which we are when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) occupies memory.
In this way, sensations are closely linked to the regions of the cortex, which distinguish primates and in particular humans.
In connection with the linguistic nature, fine degrees of feeling arise, because with the help of words and grammar, we can differentiate and categorize states in order to attribute them to others besides ourselves.
Antonio Damasio, on the other hand, believes that sensations from more primitive activities in the body’s sensory regions of the cortex and the brain stem are similar to those of Jaak Pankseep, who, however, focuses more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it could well be involved in intergenerational sensations.
In theory, I can’t argue with it, but I think it’s unproven.
Pankseep argues that what appears in rats and humans like fear probably feels like this in both cases: But how can one check whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave similarly?
A sheep flees in danger if it also feels fear?
In my eyes, mere behavioral similarity cannot yet prove equality of experience.
Although the neural comparison further helps: rats and humans have similar brain strains, but sheep do not even have a brain.
But is the brain stem responsible for sensations?
And even if you could prove it to humans, how would you prove it in rats?
I believe that rats and other mammals, maybe even sheep (who knows?), have feelings.
But I wouldn't know how to prove it.
And because their sensations are probably fundamentally different from ours (since human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I prefer to explore the emotional behavior rather than the emotional sensations of rats.
In any case, progress is gaining on the neural plane, as long as the same is measured in rats and humans.
As I do not explore language and consciousness in rats, nor do I explore sensations, I do not know if they exist.
You may think that’s short-sighted, but I’d rather go ahead than constantly running against a wall.
I am a practical emotionalist.
