Debate on bilingual education: Education in an English-speaking environment
In this edition of "Education Watch", Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the positions of candidates for bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, Senior Research Fellow in Caliphic Studies and Senior Director in Educational Sciences at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is a co-author of the book "Not as Good as You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs a School Choice".
Addressing the Spanish electorate is a complicated task.
Barack Obama’s proposals on education are a typical example of this.
Obama’s election campaign mentions that “the probability of successful completion of school by African-American and Hispanic students is lower than by white students” – which is correct.
To close this performance gap, Obama’s education plan specifically recommends, among other things, a bilingual transition phase in education for those who first learn English.
Yet the question for Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which places the emphasis on teaching in languages other than English, contradicts his interest in reducing the gap in school performance.
Take Sixth Street Prep, a primary school in eastern Los Angeles, for example.
The majority of students are Hispanic and come from low-income families.
More than a third of students, many of whom have recently been in the country, learn English.
Yet in 2008, astonishing 100 percent of fourth graders passed the state exam in Mathematics at a good level.
Also surprisingly, 93 percent of children from the fourth year of school were rated good in the English exam.
This astonishing success has been achieved by other methods than those preferred by Obama.
Sixth Street School places its emphasis on review and practice, constant control of knowledge and an attitude that does not tolerate exceptions.
In addition, the school practices the approach that the education takes place in an English-speaking environment, which is exactly the point that Obama should observe, according to the head of the school Linda Mikels.
This approach attaches importance to the almost exclusive use of the English language in professional education.
Ms. Mikels, who rejected the idea of bilingual education, told me that the school would have had a remarkable success with a student who had just come from Mexico, 12 months later they would enter the classroom and not be able to recognize him.
“It works,” she said, “it works for us.”
Would Obama take a school like the “Sixth Street Prep” as a model for other schools with a large share of Latin American and other English-learning students?
The school’s achievements would make the answer to this question easy, but the educational political positions within his own party (the national educational associations have long supported the idea of bilingual education) and his own consistent support of bilingual education make predictions about Obama’s unpredictability.
While he agrees with the point that immigrants should learn English, he has recently trivialized the issue by noting that people should stop worrying about the “English-only” legislation.
Instead, he said, "You should make sure that your child can speak Spanish."
If Obama wants to actually close the power gap, he should carefully consider educational models that work, rather than despise and trivialize them.
