Underwear - From the blood that was back safe
Hema-Quebec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its founding yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, because Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And above all, it has regained public confidence, which had been severely shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As you know, the national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross blood donation service were infected with HIV and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In view of this drama and public dissatisfaction, in February 1994, the Government of Canada launched a public investigation, initiated by Judge Horace Krever, aimed at bringing light to the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy, and drafting guidelines for such a catastrophic event.
While Judge Krever was still hesitant to submit his report, several provinces at the time set up a committee whose goal was to develop a new system for managing blood cans in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee carried out this task.
According to reports by Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, which is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian blood company to supply the other provinces and the two territories.
When Hema-Quebec started work in 1998, only 38% of people had confidence in Quebec’s blood-conserving system, Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
Through the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood cans and through work in this area over the following years, we have regained public trust," she says, before proudly stressing that by the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of the population of Quebec had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
However, Dr. Décary keeps in mind that ‘trust is something extremely fragile’.
Since its founding on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec has been acting on the precautionary principle.
At that time, we experienced the occurrence of numerous cases of the human form of cattle disease in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says this woman, who has been in charge since its founding in 1998.
And we had no idea if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
So we consulted one of the main guidelines of the reports of Kreber and Gélineau, according to which one applies exclusion measures if one does not know this and if a disease only progresses slowly, as is evident in the case of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is the case by way of a degeneration of the brain.
So in April 1999, no blood was taken from people who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, there was no doubt that this disease was transmitted through the blood.
So this event has shown us that the principle of caution that we applied makes sense.
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (NST), which make it possible to detect the presence of the virus itself directly in the blood of the donor, and not that of the antibodies against the virus, as was the case in the tests used so far.
The NSTs made it possible to shorten the incubation time that occurs between the time the person was infected and when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to a duration of less than a week.
Thus, the risk that certain donors could be infected without knowing it, and one could not recognize this, was significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmitting AIDS via a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of getting HIV-infected blood.
“In other words, this means that you would have to distribute 12 million blood cans before someone would be infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood cans each year, it would take more than 24 years for a case to occur where HIV was transmitted through a blood can.
I believe that you can feel comfortable with it these days if you get a blood transfusion or prescribe it to restore your health," says the head of management of Hema-Quebec.
“Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen can get into the system.
It was not until last year that the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the Westnil virus, is transmitted through insects through the blood.
We need to constantly monitor," Dr. Décary continues, before stressing that Hema-Quebec must provide adequate supplies in addition to a secure supply.
“The demand is increasing because the population is aging.
Because cancer-fighting treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects the blood donor network, which, on average, only 3% of Quebec's eligible blood donors belong to.
Every healthy person who is 18 years of age or older and meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who provide their blood are not accepted because, for example, they are sick with AIDS or malaria, and anyone who has traveled to a country where malaria is common is excluded from blood donation for one year.
With these 3%, we are able to get an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Lack of supplies is very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network as they get older and can no longer donate blood.
It’s hard to convince people to donate blood, but most importantly, to keep them and make them become regular donors.
Life is so hectic these days that you rarely find the time to spend an hour donating blood,” says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec delivers not only blood conserves but also human tissue, including bone transplants, heart flaps, eyeballs and skin, which is used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before being interspersed at Hema-Quebec, which also manages Quebec’s only public umbilical cord blood bank.
The umbilical cord, formerly considered biomedical waste, contains blood-rich stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposition of our thousandth umbilical cord blood sample, and we plan to take away more than a thousand each year.
“We should probably start making it available for transplantation at the beginning of next year,” Dr. Décary continues, describing this program of umbilical cord blood loss as very popular.
“Many mothers are convinced they don’t have access to it, because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and costly program in all Quebec hospitals.
