Free Opinion - The Orwellian Speech by Barrick Gold
In its September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Patrick J. Garver, Deputy Director General of the Canadian Gold Mine Barrick Gold.
This confirms, and pursues an Orwellian logic, that the world’s largest gold-winning company sought a six-million-dollar vilification lawsuit against three authors and a small, mediocre publishing house, with the aim of opening a ‘public transparent debate’.
If it is true that the judges are independent and impartial, then they do not judge on the truth, especially not in the case of libel lawsuits, but on the law.
As expected, this fundamental difference was completely concealed by Mr Garver.
Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate is to bring everyone into ruin who dares to represent one of their opposite opinions.
No matter how the trial proceeds, the authors and publishers of Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defense and fight with very unequal weapons against an army of lawyers who are paid out of the almost inexhaustible pockets of the gold mines.
The tactic of these unequal struggles, by the way, is often to ruin the defenders in order to force a consensus arrangement that will make the other side dead and also deter anyone who dares to deal with the issue again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, she should have presented her view of things to the public.
Contrary to what is going on and going on in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are usually conducted through the exchange of ideas and not through clutter.
So it would have been enough if the gold mines had disclosed their books and files and opened up a real debate, through the newspapers, media, publications and funding of independent test teams that could have brought light to this question.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to have any confidence in public opinion and wipes out the petitions and letters to support the authors of Noir Canada with a hand movement.
Could Mr Garver perhaps explain how he can ask for a 'public' debate at the same time, but at the same time misrepresent the views of this public?
Apparently, in the Vice-President's world, this word covers only the generously paid lawyers, and not the community of all Canadians; a very narrow view of the term.
In a democracy, even offenders have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn’t understand – or doesn’t want to understand – is that the public supporting Noir Canada’s authors and publishers does this mainly because they reject the brutal stance of the gold mines.
This public is ready to listen to and judge Barrick, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, and not within a framework that many perceive as a snail suit (in the course of the <0x60>public debate' more... Barrick Gold has just made a request to the authors of Noir Canada, not to address them).
Apart from Mr. Garver’s surreal speech, Barrick Gold’s lawsuit is a direct attack on the freedom of academic research and truth-finding that are fundamental to any democratic society.
It completely denies the right to cite credible sources and to discuss facts and interpretations that form the basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible in a country like Canada to explore and discuss issues that do not please the rich companies of the world, then who else can do that?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, he could lead it by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
She has a right to answer.
The university environment to which we belong has long been known to get hold of debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s disproportionate lawsuit clearly shows that she, contrary to what she pretends, has no desire for a transparent debate.
This is a loss to the university world, as well as to the public debate, and it will be time for governments to take action to curb these kinds of unjustified lawsuits.
