The Bush administration and the top congressmen, Republicans and Democrats alike, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the most comprehensive economic recovery plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan, which aims to stop the financial crisis that has rocked Wall Street for months, has yet to be adopted by the two chambers of Congress.
The main contents are: better control of MPs over the practical application of the plan, new mechanisms to secure the repayment of the public funds used, new provisions to reduce the number of houses seized due to the company's payment residuals, as well as the right to overpay the salaries.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, Speaker of the Chamber of Deputies Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican representative present at the negotiations, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news yesterday, minutes after midnight, after a two-day negotiation marathon.
“We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be market-effective,” Bush administration spokesman Henry Paulson said in a statement.
“Everything was done to protect the real economy and the American people from the Wall Street price crisis,” she said.
“This is the fundamental point: if we don’t do that, the trauma, the chaos and the unrest in the daily lives of Americans will be enormous,” Republican Judd Gregg said.
Negotiations had accelerated over the last two hours, out of fear of the effect that a relapse would have had on the mood of investors.
The deadline that had been agreed was the market opening this morning.
The two U.S. presidential candidates, who only took part in the negotiations lately, were more likely to be in favour of the agreement, but without failing to express their dissatisfaction with the need to meet them in this extreme way.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama insisted on the addition of certain provisions for agreement, especially those that would allow owners to keep their homes, and those that concern the salaries of the executives of the state-saved companies.
“If you ask taxpayers to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of certain people, that is nothing to be congratulated on.
