It was a group of Republican MPs who last week failed the first attempt at a settlement.
Since the Democrats have accepted that certain “toxic” assets of the oppressed companies should only be secured by the government and not bought, one believes to escape the dead end.
To round out the perspective for everyone in Congress, a provision has also been added that if the government were to make losses with this program within five years, it would then be able to raise new taxes to recover its capital employed.
The new plan envisages the payment of a first sum of $250 billion, to which another $100 billion can be added if the president deems it necessary.
The payment of another $350 billion has to be passed by Congress in a re-vote.
In return for his help, Washington receives shares in the backed companies that make dividends in the event of earnings, and that can sell it again when the storm has passed.
