Neurologists and economic researchers at the University of New York have now managed to discover the neurological-economic basis of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, do not want to be beaten and are therefore willing to pay even excessive prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers should play lottery while the other participated in a playful action – in both cases, the active brain regions of the subjects were examined using functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI).
In both games, the participants were able to win money, however, an increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the cerebral cortex, was measured in the losers of the auction, in which overcoming the opponent plays an essential role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore thought that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the striatum.
In order to support their thesis, the economists in the research group have also undertaken research to track the money.
In this case, three groups should compete against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their efforts.
Another group was also promised a $15 reward in case they emerged as the winner of the game.
The third group received $15 before the auction, which was also lost in the event of a lost game.
So the difference between the two groups was just that the emphasis on one was on winning, while the other was on losing.
However, as evidence of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, the members of the “against the loss” group were willing to make higher bets than those in the control or the “win” group.
“These results cannot be deduced from any previous economic theory.
This is because they have justified the behaviors observed at auctions so far only with the joy of winning or avoiding risk.
The contradiction between these two theories was resolved thanks to the imaging neurological processes, so we now have a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should I see a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary, this chronic liver disease is among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected is estimated to be one hundred thousand in this country, but only seven thousand are being treated, which is because the patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver diseases triggered by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - inflammation of the liver and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and diseases differ from each other.
Depending on the pathogen, the hepatitis viruses are spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example, through contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other body fluids (such as sperm, vaginal secretions or saliva).
Travelers are advised to get vaccinated against viruses A and B, there is no vaccine against virus C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear about two to three weeks after eating the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain, and vomiting.
After that, yellowing occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the stool becomes light, the urine darkens, and the recovery can last up to two to three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die annually from hepatitis B-induced, far more serious diseases such as liver cancer and cirrhosis of the liver.
The main reason for this is that, according to estimates, only one in ten infected is in drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated it can lead to liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected do not even know about their disease, since the pathogen secretly destroys the liver cells - in many cases, the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular inspections, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more common: those who underwent a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooed.
Currently, the number of people with chronic hepatitis C is estimated to be 200 million worldwide.
Since the disease is already detectable with a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to visit the doctor at the first signs of unknown origin.
Timely detected, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, thereby curing the risk of infection and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30th is the World Hepatitis Day, which was held for the first time by patient representations worldwide in 2004.
The aim of the action is to strengthen awareness of these chronic liver inflammation caused by viruses, their emergence and the importance of early detection.
