As recent research results prove, religious faith acts as a kind of “pain remedy” that is already supposed to have facilitated the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University conducted an interesting experiment: It was investigated to what extent faith in God influences human pain, the British newspaper "Telegraph" reported.
In the course of the rather bizarre investigation, 12 believers and atheists each received electric shocks while studying a painting of the Mother of God.
As the results showed, the believers were able to turn off most of the pain.
Using brain scanning technology, it was even possible to prove that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for regulating pain.
The study was the first in a research project, in which, in addition to scientists, philosophers and theologians from various departments of the University participate.
During the test, a flashing device was attached to the left hand, which gave off the electric shocks.
Participants were asked to focus heavily on two paintings: on the one hand an image of the Mother of God, painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century, and on the other Leonardo da Vinci's "Lady with the Hermelin".
The researchers hoped that the appearance of the Virgin Mary among the faithful would evoke some sort of religious trance, while choosing da Vinci’s image because it was hardly different from the other paintings and was felt as reassuring.
The subjects each spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during that time received a total of 20 electric shocks in four stages, while they were supposed to look at either the religious or the other painting.
The Catholics reported that they felt “safe” in the presence of the Mother of God, as if they were “saved” and felt “peace and peace.”
While viewing the religious painting, they reported 12% less pain than when they had Leonardo’s work in front of their eyes.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also took part in the experiment, said that similar effects could also be elicited with other, highly effective images also in the atheists, you just had to find the corresponding photo.
“We would have to find an image that triggers very positive feelings, such as a mother or a father,” he said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
“Practicing faith should change our personality, and it does in many cases,” Wright said.
After these excellent results, only the question remains, what effect would a Madonna image of Leonardo or another comparable painter have on the pain regulation of believers.
Would the high-quality Virgin Mary achieve even better results?
