Intelligent car mimics the flight of the Hummels
What would be the best way to develop new technologies to prevent accidents if not to imitate the obstacle sensors from nature?
For example, those of the bees.
At CEATEC in Japan, an astonishing project was presented, in which Nissan engineers from Hummeln were inspired to create new accident-preventing systems.
In collaboration with Tokyo University, Nissan has built the BR23C autorobot-driven biomimetic system, a mini car equipped with the characteristics of the bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own, oval "private area", which is very similar to our own "protection shield", said Kazuhhiro Doi, Product Manager for Technology PR and Research Development, at the exhibition.
The bee’s composite eye, which can see in any direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role in this.
In order to imitate the function of the composite eye, the researchers came up with the idea of a laser-controlled distance meter.
It identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C in a 180-degree field of view within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor to the board, which immediately initiates the collision prevention process.
The obstacle is recorded in fractions of a second, and the autorobot immediately changes course, similar to the movement of the bees by rotating the tires at the appropriate angle.
Unlike previous systems, this maneuver takes place purely instinctively.
“If it wasn’t, the autorobot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the autorobot project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield – a layer that is still considered inevitable within the accidents currently.
The whole process must reflect the behavior of the bees when they avoid other bees.
And that has to happen in a fraction of a second.
However, the avoidance, unlike the bees, can not take place up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, and that is only in the direction of the reversibility of the tires.
While the bees here are endlessly open to avoiding other bees, the researchers were only able to use the rotary motion, or acceleration and braking, in the autorobot.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy efficient, and therefore have a longer service life than conventional lithium ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it depends on the instinctive, intelligent response, and less on the processing of the data, and even less on the ability to store it.
This device only needs to process a few inputs per second and respond accordingly.
It does not need to store them, or produce an intuitive, logical response using earlier manoeuvres, so that it constantly requires only a handful of KB memory.
It does not require any gigabytes and megabytes of hard memory.
This is the first step in the development of immediate collision avoidance technology, which Nissan estimates will be in production as standard within the next ten years.
Another application could find the technology in GPS satellite navigation by consciously steering the driver around obstacles and thus leading him to the destination.
