Nobel Prize in Economics goes to Paul Krugman
The Nobel Prize in Economics is given to the American Paul Krugman for his analysis of trade patterns and the settlement of economic activities.
The 55-year-old Krugman is a Neokeynesian who teaches at Princeton University and is known for his regular articles for the New York Times.
Krugman is one of the biggest critics of the Bush administration’s economic and foreign policy.
A few months after the September 11, 2001 attacks, during the days of the Enron collapse, Krugman had claimed in a New York Times headline that this second event was more decisive for U.S. history than the assassinations.
A prediction that received quite a bit of controversy in response and was kept to the economist years later, but today turns out to be quite correct.
“I am surprised and shocked at how quickly the memory of the scandals as part of the collapses of Enron or Worldcom has disappeared from the public eye,” Krugman said in a statement.
According to Lorenzo Bini Smaghi of the Executive Committee of the European Central Bank, Krugman is a “great economist”, but also a banalizer with a “very aggressive style, especially against the excessive liberalism of the Bush administration.”
Open Office, the third version of the "Anti-Microsoft" package
The day of release of OpenOffice.org 3.0 has come; the open source software is gaining as a free replacement for Microsoft Office an increasing number of users, both at home and in the office, both among freelancers and in the public administration.
After a year of intensive work by the volunteer developers, which is monitored by SUN Microsystems, the new Open Office now presents itself to the public with some novelties: besides a revised and now more spartanly designed start menu, the new OS is now finally the new OS for guaranteed and the new OS for Mac OS OS.
Attention was also paid to the compatibility with Microsoft Office 2007, whose new formats (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx) can be read by OpenOffice.
Interesting are also some new features, such as those that allow you to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations, which for example makes sending via email easier. This also includes the possibility to import PDF files into graphics editing modules and at the same time the original appearance of the page.
Thus, you can now also generate "hybrid" PDF files, which extend the typical graphics of the Adobe format by the elements of a table and a word processing system.
Collaboration is one of the most improved elements of the applications: tables can now be edited by different users in multiple hands, avoiding conflicts in the event of changes; in the case of the word processing system, each editor is assigned a query to ensure a better correction procedure.
Some companies are about to publish various features of OpenOffice on the Internet (on the cloud), while in the coming weeks the final result is to be made public.
The Italian version is available for download at the following link: http://en.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html, so it follows the English version, which has been on the mirrors since Friday.
In addition to Windows and Mac OS, the program is also available for the Linux operating system.
On request, you can send the installation CD to your home or office.
While free will can be an incentive for the spread of the program in private households, it is also in the business area where OpenOffice could succeed: after all, various public administration institutions and schools have already switched to OpenOffice.
In fact, it does not even lack a training offer, which means an optimal help for small and medium-sized enterprises, and thus even opens up business prospects.
OpenOffice consists of five main components: Writer, the Word corresponding text creation program; Calc, the spreadsheet program that aims to displace Excel; Impress, to create presentations such as with PowerPoint; Dbase to run databases instead of the more familiar Access; and finally, Gramow.
The goal for 2008 is to reach 5 million downloads – a goal that can easily exceed 3 million and 600 thousand already reached.
