Farewell to the old cinema Paradiso – the cities close their historic cinemas
The historic cinemas close due to the favoured multiplex cinemas.
“A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes.”
This image of director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is currently happening in the great urban centres of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of exclusion of cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multi-room complexes in the periphery, means in the long run the death for the one-room cinema in the center. A process that not only appears inevitable and irreversible, but also the traits of a cultural crime.
"It's like losing a friend with whom you've left a street full of emotions," says the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso", who presented him with an Oscar and the Grand Prix of Cannes 20 years ago, for which he won a prize for Cannes.
The figures provided by the Anec, the central trade association, speak a clear language: in the last five years, the huge amount of 316 traditional cinemas have had to close; these signs mostly paid for the cinemas in the major cities: 10 in Florence and 5 in Pamoin and 5 in Milan, 9 in Bologna, Naples.
The most affected regions include the Emilia-Romagna with 82 cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This shows that the main culprits are the multiplex cinemas, because it is these three regions in which the largest number of these modern cinemas has been recorded: with 195 in the last 5 years Lombardy leads the lists, 81 are in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The business has evolved in an irrational way," says Paolo Protti, the president of the Anec, "it is useful that new structures also arise, but in the first place is the preservation of the already existing, because a hall in the city closes to a multi-storey, not all its regular customers are ready to arrive.
And here the lack of budget for the trade union fund remains out of consideration: the debt burden recorded by the state is about 10 million euros.
It is a disgrace from the ethical-moral point of view that the government does not comply with existing laws.
To maintain the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros a year would be needed".
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city to decide, because of fears about the old cinemas, to protect them through an agreement between the community and the Anec; it is the first agreement of its kind in Italy, which aims to protect and support the traditional cinemas as a perriel in the Zen, and so on.
The measures envisaged also include tax advantages for cinema operators as well as benefits for the public in terms of local transport: it will be allowed to drive to the traffic-restricted areas of the centre and also to park at cheaper parking fees.
“It’s an exciting initiative,” says Giuseppe Tornatore, “I hope other cities will follow our example and also design new concepts.
Of course, we also need better audio and video equipment to be able to align something against the superpower of multiplex rooms, because after all, today’s audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema has always been an important topic for me: the closure of the "supercinema" of Baghiera, the place of my childhood and youth, was the decisive point that led me to found the "Nuovo cinema Paradiso", even though I have been playing it for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years; when I pass the Rialto or the Quirinale in the Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn to the side to not have to see the dusty posters.
