When the energy comes out of the waves, suddenly the big ones run up.
It is a non-successful source of money that covers over 70% of the planet’s surface, and only now do the big energy companies of the world seem to understand this.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable sources of energy that everyone is now looking at, and also looking to occupy, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and studied for 70 years; not by chance, these studies have intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil broke down around 1980, the idea of marine energy was forgotten, but now environmental organizations and the rising price of oil are pushing for new impulses in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the world’s energy needs could be covered by the energy generated by ocean waves.
This is equivalent to twice the energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, the currents and tides are also added.
Giants in attack.
The first company to focus on marine energy is Enersis, which signed a contract in 2005 to build a power plant in the north of Portugal.
When this message was published, it appeared to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies from the traditional energy industry are relying on marine energy production.
“Chevron is investigating these technologies,” said a spokesman for a company known to the US giant in the Wall Street Journal, “and weighs the possibility of working with us.”
This is about obtaining an approval from the American Energy Commission, which is necessary to start a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a sign not to be underestimated, especially given the fact that oil is still being promoted by the United States in Alaska, and President Bush recently launched plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, the companies Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey are also investing in the new industry; even the details are not known, as observers say of an increasing interest.
Techniques worthy of improvement.
Experts are talking about a technology that is still in its infancy, not least because the last doubts have not yet been clarified by environmentalists.
So far, projects such as those in Portugal and Scotland are rather small and do not seem to be causing serious ecological problems.
However, in order to produce energy on a large scale, it requires technologies with far greater impact on the environment.
There are several ways: for example, Ocean Power uses a system of interconnected bojens.
The thrust of the shafts, which moves the bojens up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the float via pistons and cylinders.
This drives a turbine, which in turn drives a generator.
The current is then sent to the coast via underwater lines.
So far, there are four planned installations of this type, which are only waiting for state approval, some of which could also be used for military installations.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces energy for a department store and a parking lot using underwater turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movements during the tides drive the turbines, which feeds the generator through the resulting rotational movement.
According to Verdant, a long line of potential clients are already waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Electricity Extraction Research, the potential that is presently in the tides is of particular interest.
Although this is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are better predictable than wind currents, solar radiation and also waves, and therefore a more reliable source of electricity.
It is precisely the tidal energy that led states such as New York, Maine and Alaska as well as other coastal states to invest $7.5 million in 2008 – up to $35 million is already planned for 2009.
